# Zesu

## Scope

The Zesu documentation site covers Zesu, the Consensys stateless ZK execution client. The
documentation is a single product area (no separate trees for different deployment modes).

When describing Zesu in prose, do not invent capabilities, performance characteristics, or
component names that you have not verified against the Zesu codebase or an official Consensys
reference. If you are uncertain about a behavior or option, flag it for review rather than
stating it as fact.

## Content organization

| Folder              | Content type                                                |
|---------------------|-------------------------------------------------------------|
| `concepts/`         | Explanation (architecture, design decisions, how features work) |
| `get-started/`      | Onboarding (system requirements, installation, quickstart)  |
| `how-to/`           | How-to guides (configure and operate Zesu)                  |
| `reference/`        | Reference material (CLI options and other lookups)          |
| `troubleshooting.md`| Top-level page listing common problems and fixes            |

Follow the structural expectations in `content-types.mdc` for each folder.

## Reference conventions

### CLI options

The format for `docs/reference/cli-options.md` is not yet defined. When the first batch of
options is added, the documentation team should agree on a convention (for example, heading
style, parameter format, whether to show defaults and environment variable equivalents) and
update this rule with the chosen format. Until then, do not invent a convention; ask the
documentation team before adding entries.

## Configuration examples

Whether Zesu supports a configuration file (and, if so, in what format) has not been documented
here. Do not invent a configuration file format or assume one exists.

When configuration patterns are confirmed, update this section to describe them. Until then,
the only universally applicable rule is:

- Always include a language tag on code blocks (for example, `bash`, `toml`, `yaml`, `json`).

## Sidebar

The sidebar is **manually defined** in `sidebars.js`. When adding a new page, add its ID to the
correct category in `sidebars.js` in the same PR. The page ID is the path under `docs/` without
the file extension (for example, `how-to/configure`).

See `contributor-workflow.mdc` for the full sidebar update workflow.
